ian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortagne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Francoise, Herve, Marcel, Philippe, Pierre.","French: topographic name for someone who lived on or near a hill, from Old French <i>montaine</i> ‘hill, (small) mountain’; or a habitational name from any of several places called (La) Montagne, named with the same word.","Shortened form of French   Lamontagne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mountain","meanings":["English (Yorkshire; of Norman origin): topographic name from Middle English <i>mountaine</i> ‘mountain’ (Old French <i>montagne</i>). See   Montagne  .","Irish: either of Norman origin, as 1 above, or a variant of   Manton  .","English: variant of <b>Monkton</b> a habitational name from Monkton (Kent, Somerset), Moor Monkton and Nun Monkton (Yorkshire), Bishop Monkton (Yorkshire), or any of numerous other places called Monkton, named with Old English <i>munuc</i> ‘monk’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Lamontagne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Marcel, Emile, Pierre, Aime, Andre, Fernand, Normand, Gaston, Ovide, Achille.","French:","habitational name for someone from any of several places called La Montagne, or a variant of the topographic name   Montagne   1, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]}]},{"name":"Tournai","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Turney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Turney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","habi